    "Interpretation: Distribution of Annual_Income\n",
    "\n",
    "The histogram shows that Annual_Income is approximately normally distributed, with a single clear peak around the middle of the income range.\n",
    "\n",
    "🔹 Key observations\n",
    "\n",
    "Shape:\n",
    "The distribution is bell-shaped, indicating a near-normal distribution. This suggests that most customers earn around the average income level.\n",
    "\n",
    "Center:\n",
    "The highest concentration of customers falls roughly between ₦60,000 and ₦90,000, indicating this is the typical income range within the dataset.\n",
    "\n",
    "Skewness:\n",
    "The distribution appears slightly right-skewed, as there are fewer customers with very high incomes extending toward the upper end (above ₦120,000). This suggests the presence of higher-income customers, but they are relatively rare.\n",
    "\n",
    "Spread:\n",
    "Annual income values are widely spread, ranging from very low incomes to high incomes (up to about ₦140,000), indicating income diversity among customers.\n",
    "\n",
    "Outliers:\n",
    "A small number of observations at both the lower and upper extremes may represent potential outliers, especially high-income customers who could influence averages and clustering results.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "Implication for analysis\n",
    "\n",
    "The near-normal distribution means scaling and K-Means clustering are appropriate.\n",
    "\n",
    "Slight right skew and extreme values suggest that standardization (scaling) is important to prevent high incomes from dominating the clustering process.\n",
    "\n",
    "High-income outliers may represent premium or high-value customers, which could be meaningful in segmentation."
