   "source": [
    "BUSINESS INTERPRETATION"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "51d83ae3-586f-48cf-b1a6-d24b018a6fd1",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Since our Annual Income and Monthly Spend have high standard deviations, these will be the strongest indicators of financial value, while Visits and Loyalty Score track the emotional connection to the brand.\n",
    "\n",
    "1. Behaviors Suggesting “High Value”\n",
    "High value isn't just about having a high Annual_Income; it’s about how that income translates into consistent behavior.\n",
    "\n",
    "The \"Major Advocates\": Customers with high Loyalty_Score and high Store_Visits_Per_Month. These users aren't just spending; they are physically engaging with the brand frequently.\n",
    "\n",
    "The \"Premium Digital Shoppers\": High Monthly_Spend combined with high Online_Visits_Per_Month. These are efficient, high-revenue customers who likely have a high Annual_Income.\n",
    "\n",
    "The \"Stable Spenders\": If you see low variance in Monthly_Spend but a high average, these are your most predictable revenue sources.\n",
    "\n",
    "2. Patterns Indicating Churn or Disengagement \n",
    "Churn (customers leaving) usually shows up in the behavior metrics before the spending stops.\n",
    "\n",
    "The \"Digital Ghosting\" Pattern: A sharp drop in Online_Visits_Per_Month while Monthly_Spend remains temporarily steady. This often precedes a total stop in spending.\n",
    "\n",
    "The \"Low-Value Loyalty\": A high Loyalty_Score but very low Monthly_Spend and Store_Visits. This suggests a customer who \"likes\" the brand but has stopped findng reasons to buy.\n",
    "\n",
    "The \"Income-Spend Mismatch\": Customers with high Annual_Income but bottom-tier Loyalty_Score and Monthly_Spend. This indicates the brand is failing to capture the \"wallet share\" of a customer who clearly has the means to buy."
   ]
  },
